Read in the data.

df_raw <- readr::read_csv(data_url, col_names = TRUE)

Separate the variables associated with Step 1.

df_step1_inputs <- df_raw %>% select(xA, xB, x01:x06, response_1)

Separate the variables associated with the Option B classification formulation. The outcome_2 variable is converted to a factor with a specific ordering of the levels. This ordering is used when modeling in caret to make sure everyone predicts the Fail class as the “positive” class in the confusion matrix.

df_step2_B_inputs <- df_raw %>% select(xA, xB, response_1, x07:x11, outcome_2) %>% 
  mutate(outcome_2 = factor(outcome_2, levels = c('Fail', 'Pass')))

Separate the variables associated with the Option A classification formulation. The outcome_2 variable is again converted to a factor with a specific ordering of the levels.

df_step2_A_inputs <- df_raw %>% select(xA, xB, x01:x11, outcome_2) %>% 
  mutate(outcome_2 = factor(outcome_2, levels = c('Fail', 'Pass')))

Change data types for the whole data frame to perform EDA.

df <- df_raw %>% 
  mutate(xA = as.factor(xA),
         xB = as.factor(xB),
         outcome_2 = factor(outcome_2, levels = c('Fail', 'Pass')))

Standardize the data.

get_standardized <- function(df) {
  predict(preProcess(df, method = c('center', 'scale')), df) 
}

Some helper functions to get the features of a particular type.

get_CATEGORICAL_features_list <- function(df){
  colnames(df)[grepl('factor|logical|character',sapply(df,class))]
}
get_CONTINIOUS_features_list <- function(df){
  df %>% select(-get_CATEGORICAL_features_list(df)) %>% colnames()
}

Helper Functions

# helper function
binomial_smooth <- function(...) {
  geom_smooth(method = 'glm', method.args = list(family = 'binomial'), ...)
}

It seems like the outcome_2 does not impact the distribution of a particular continuous input variable; there are, most likely, more complex relationships present.

Check for multimodal behavior with violin plots.

df_step2_B_inputs %>% 
  select(c(outcome_2, get_CONTINIOUS_features_list(df_step2_B_inputs))) %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column() %>% 
  tidyr::gather(key = 'key', value = 'value', -rowid, -outcome_2) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = outcome_2, y = value)) +
  geom_violin(mapping = aes(group = interaction(key, outcome_2),
                             fill = outcome_2)) +
  stat_summary(fun.data = 'mean_se', color = 'white') +
  facet_grid(outcome_2 ~ .) +
  facet_wrap(~key, scales = 'free') +
  theme_bw()

The variables seem to be roughly unimodal.

Break up the continuous variables by the binary outcome

df %>% 
  select(c(outcome_2, get_CONTINIOUS_features_list(df))) %>%
  tibble::rowid_to_column() %>% 
  tidyr::gather(key = 'key', value = 'value', -rowid, -outcome_2) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = value)) +
  geom_freqpoly(bins = 25,
                mapping = aes(color = outcome_2,
                              y = stat(density)),
                size = 1.) +
  facet_wrap(~key, scales = "free_y") +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.y = element_blank())

The distribution of the results is the same regardless of the class.
